statement:
The *sum rule* states that

$${\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}\left[f(x)+g(x)\right] = f'(x) + g'(x)$$

### Proof {#proof .unnumbered}

See the .

### Examples {#examples .unnumbered}

$$\begin{aligned}
{\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}(x + 1) & = & {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}x + {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}1 = 1 \\
{\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}(x^2 - 3x + 2) & = & {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}x^2 + {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}(-3x) + {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}(2) = 2x-3 \\
{\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}(\sin x + \cos x) & = & {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}\sin x + {\ensuremath{\frac{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}}{{\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}x}}}}}\cos x = \cos x - \sin x\end{aligned}$$
